{"text":"What if the Aztecs had successfully repelled the Spanish conquistadors?","lang":"en","__index_level_0__":51,"answer":"nobody knows for sure, but it' 's possible that they could have continued to thrive and fl th in their new world. The Aztecs were highly skilled at building and maintaining their infrastructure, including their cities, temples, and their irrigation systems. They also had a strong sense of community and social structure, with a complex system of governance and religion. If they had been able to fend off the Spanish invaders, they may have been able to continue to thrive and thrive in their new world.\n\nThe Aztecs were highly skilled at building and maintaining their infrastructure, including their cities, temples, and their irrigation system. They also had a strong sense of community and social structure, with a complex system of governance and religion. They had a complex system of governance and religion, with a powerful leader who was revered and respected throughout the land. This would have allowed them to unite and defend their people more effectively, and potentially avoid the collapse of their society that occurred after the Spanish invasion.\n\nIf the Aztecs had been able to fend off the Spanish invader, they may have been able to continue to thrive and thrive in their new world. They may have been able to continue to build and maintain their infrastructure, including their cities, temples, and their irrigation system. They may have also been able to continue to thrive and thrive in their new world, without the threat of colonization h hanging over them. This could have allowed them to focus on their own development and growth, rather than having to constantly fight off the invaders.\n\nIt is also possible that the Aztecs could have continued to thrive and thrive in their new world even despite the Spanish invasion. Despite the fact that the Spanish were more advanced than the Aztecs in many ways, the Aztecs were highly skilled at b